<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Cost Factors</p>
    <h2>What affects wine cooler repair cost in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127774;</div><h3>LA ambient temperature</h3><p>LA summers push ambient temperatures in unconditioned garages and rooms to 85&ndash;100&deg;F. Thermoelectric units aren&rsquo;t designed for this &mdash; they appear broken when they&rsquo;re overwhelmed. Compressor units run harder and wear faster. We assess ambient conditions before diagnosing components.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#9889;</div><h3>Thermoelectric repair economics</h3><p>A Peltier module replacement on a 6-bottle thermoelectric unit may cost more than the unit itself. We give you the honest math before ordering parts. On 24-bottle and larger thermoelectric units, repair often makes sense.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127863;</div><h3>Vibration sensitivity</h3><p>Wine storage requires minimal vibration &mdash; vibration disturbs sediment and accelerates aging. Compressor noise and vibration repairs are taken seriously on wine storage units. We confirm quiet operation before leaving.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127991;</div><h3>Brand and OEM parts</h3><p>Sub-Zero and Liebherr use proprietary compressor systems with premium OEM parts. Budget brands use generic Peltier modules. Parts are quoted separately so you see the real cost difference between brands.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127968;</div><h3>Installation location in LA</h3><p>Wine coolers installed in unconditioned garages (common in the Valley and IE), near windows in direct sunlight, or in spaces with poor ventilation struggle in LA. We advise on installation improvements alongside the repair.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#9874;</div><h3>Refrigerant handling</h3><p>Compressor wine cooler refrigerant work requires an EPA-certified technician. Refrigerant leaks are quoted separately as the refrigerant charge and leak repair are distinct from labor on the component failure.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a wine cooler, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">The answer depends heavily on the type and size. We give you the honest math after diagnosis.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Compressor unit &mdash; fan, thermistor, or door gasket failure</li>
          <li>Sub-Zero, Liebherr, or EuroCave &mdash; these last 15&ndash;20 years</li>
          <li>Built-in unit &mdash; replacement requires counter/cabinet work</li>
          <li>Large thermoelectric (24+ bottles) with fan failure only</li>
          <li>Total repair under 50% of replacement value</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Small thermoelectric unit with Peltier failure</li>
          <li>Compressor failure on a budget unit under $300</li>
          <li>Unit placed in hot unconditioned space &mdash; root cause not fixable</li>
          <li>Parts discontinued with no OEM availability</li>
          <li>Multiple simultaneous failures</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

