    <h2>Questions about wine cooler repair costs in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much does wine cooler repair cost in Los Angeles?</div><div class="faq-a">Labor runs $150&ndash;$440 depending on the type and failure. Compressor units run $200&ndash;$440, thermoelectric units $150&ndash;$300. Sub-Zero and Liebherr run $280&ndash;$560+. Parts are quoted separately. The $89 diagnostic fee applies to the repair total when you approve the work.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Why is my wine cooler not cooling in Los Angeles?</div><div class="faq-a">In LA, ambient temperature is often the root cause. Thermoelectric units are designed for ambient temperatures below 75&ndash;80&deg;F &mdash; a garage in the Valley or IE can exceed that in summer, making the unit appear broken. We assess ambient conditions before diagnosing components. Sometimes the fix is relocation, not repair.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is it worth repairing a thermoelectric wine cooler?</div><div class="faq-a">It depends on the size and failure. A small thermoelectric unit (6&ndash;12 bottles) with a failed Peltier module may cost more to repair than replace. A fan failure on any thermoelectric unit is almost always worth fixing. We give you the honest math after diagnosis before ordering any parts.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Why do you quote labor and parts separately?</div><div class="faq-a">Many LA repair companies use flat-rate BlueBook pricing. A thermoelectric fan replacement and a Sub-Zero compressor replacement are completely different jobs. We quote separately so the price reflects your actual repair &mdash; and we discuss repair vs. replace economics on thermoelectric units before proceeding.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Are parts included in the quoted labor price?</div><div class="faq-a">No &mdash; all prices on this page are labor only. Parts quoted separately after diagnosis. Refrigerant recharging (if needed) is quoted as a separate line item. OEM parts wherever available.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What is the $89 diagnostic fee?</div><div class="faq-a">We charge $89 to come out and diagnose the problem, including ambient temperature assessment and repair vs. replace economics review. That fee applies to the repair total when you approve the work. If you decide not to repair, you pay $89 and we leave.</div></div>
